The paper discusses security challenges in software-defined wireless networks (SDWNs) and proposes a novel security protocol based on physical unclonable functions (PUFs) to enhance authentication security. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) sub-category. Additionally, the paper focuses on the limited power and computation capability available at IoT devices, which suggests that it may also belong to the cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of Resistive Random Access Memory (ReRAM) in developing PUFs, which suggests that it may belong to the cs.IT (Information Theory) sub-category. Furthermore, the paper discusses the centralized management and decision-making approach in SDWNs, which suggests that it may also belong to the cs.SY (Systems and Control) sub-category. Finally, the paper proposes a novel approach of multi-states to reduce potential errors in challenge-response pairs of PUFs being tested in different situations, which suggests that it may also belong to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category.
